Method Detail

mapAllSqlProperties

private void mapAllSqlProperties(java.lang.String ownerName)

Map all the SQL columns and inherited columns in the shared map of properties keyed on name. The getSqlColumnName() method (through the mapSqlPropertyNames() method) uses this map to generate unique column names on demand. The method indexes both the property name and the explicit name (tagged value name) for all properties, since SQL column names may be explicit.

SQL columns come from various sources:

  • generated key properties
  • local attributes
  • to-one association attributes (not objects)
  • inherited columns (any of the above in a superclass)
The to-many association attributes do not correspond to SQL columns, and the generator ignores all association object (association end) properties.

The SQL column name comes from one of four possible situations:

  1. explicit name with prefix to disambiguate duplicate names
  2. property name with prefix to disambiguate duplicate names if there is no explicit name
  3. explicit name if there is no duplication
  4. property name if there is no explicit name and no duplication
Putting an explicit name on a property thus forces the use of that name for the SQL column corresponding to the property unless there is a duplicate occurrence of the name in another property, in which case the generator uses the prefix to disambiguate the name.

Parameters:
ownerName - the name of the DTO that owns the properties
See Also:
getUniqueName(), mapSqlPropertyNames(String), getSqlColumnName()

public java.lang.String getSqlColumnName()
Description copied from class: Property

That is, if there is an explicit name, that is the SQL column name, regardless of duplication, and prefixing only occurs if there is no explicit name.

getUniqueName

public java.lang.String getUniqueName()
Description copied from class: Property

Gets a unique name for the property.

  1. If the property is not an association end, use the property name.

  2. Otherwise, if there is an explicit name for the property, and that makes the name unique, use that.

  3. Otherwise, if there is an explicit name for the property that is not unique, prefix the explicit name with the prefix.

  4. Otherwise, prefix the name with the prefix.

It is still possible for the name to clash if two derived names come out the same (as name comparison is done only to the original names, not to the derived names). Such errors will require renaming the property by changing either the property name or the explicit name in the tagged value.

Specified by:
getUniqueName in class Property

isAssociationAttribute

public boolean isAssociationAttribute()
Is this property an "association attribute", meaning a data member that tracks the individual attribute key values for lookup in the database? These attributes have slightly different name resolution. This method uses the source to identify properties coming from the nested strategy that produces such attributes. There are several variations on the association attribute:
  • the association foreign key attribute
  • the to-one association attribute property
  • the explicit association key
  • the inherited association attribute property

Returns:
true if the source indicates this is an association attribute
